{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_019wEHE44AnxFkZSyFKez2Gx","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the issue clearly. The precondition `apply` does the following:\n1. Creates the namespace and deploys MongoDB\n2. Initializes the replica set with 3 correct members\n3. Waits for a primary\n4. **BREAKS member 1's host to `mongodb-replica-1.mongo-wrong.svc.cluster.local:27017`** (a fault)\n5. Inserts data\n\nSo the fault has been injected - member 1 has a wrong hostname `mongodb-replica-1.mongo-wrong.svc.cluster.local:27017` instead of `mongodb-replica-1.mongodb-replica-svc.mongodb.svc.cluster.local:27017`.\nThe probe phase detected the pod was already running, so it skipped the apply step entirely. This means the fault from a previous test run is still active—the wrong hostname for member 1 persists from before.\n\nBut looking at the current replica set status, all three members show as healthy with the correct hostnames, which suggests either the fault was already remedied or something else is going on. Let me trace through what actually happened: the first precondition's probe succeeded (skipping the destructive apply), then the second precondition inserted seed data successfully. So the fault wasn't re-injected this time, yet the task description claims the replica set should be unhealthy.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2618,"cache_read_input_tokens":35982,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2618},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"edeae7cc-187c-4c0f-ada5-bcb678eeb9f3","uuid":"1f4b77fe-d0ce-47ee-8ef6-b20615fb9768","request_id":"req_011CcLVMmxZA5DvUDT8cgxa6"}
